  "prompt": "What is greed according to Einstein?",
  "response": "Albert Einstein did not specifically define greed in a widely-known quote or text. However, his thoughts on social issues, ethics, and human behavior often reflect a disdain for excessive materialism and selfishness.\n\nEinstein believed in a life dedicated to the well-being of humanity rather than the pursuit of wealth. He often emphasized the importance of kindness, generosity, and communal responsibility. This can be inferred from his various writings and speeches where he criticized the pursuit of wealth and power at the expense of ethical and moral values.\n\nFor example, Einstein once said, \u201cA hundred times every day I remind myself that my inner and outer life depend on the labors of other men, living and dead, and that I must exert myself in order to give in the same measure as I have received and am still receiving.\u201d This quote reflects his belief in mutual support and contributing to the common good, countering the notion of greed.",
